{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"685887fb-3299-4e66-841f-586ff9e72f2a","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your C# server must use the **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If you're using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, call `.WithStdioServerTransport()` in your host builder.\n- Avoid writing logs to stdout — use stderr or a file instead, so you don't corrupt the MCP protocol stream.\n- If you prefer running a pre-built binary, replace the command with `\"dotnet\"` + `[\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]`, or point directly to a published executable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0ded110b-e3f6-40e4-827c-db243a55e87d","outputTokens":288,"requestId":"CC33:1E21:6C21AD2:7895C10:69EAC14F"},"id":"d6ba00de-c8bf-4291-8a0f-99afb3662567","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:03:20.728Z","parentId":"38ebce49-2a3d-45e6-acf5-b5db886b3c48"}
